  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money will you have to pay to try each and every combination of Subway sandwiches?",
  "response": "Calculating the cost of trying every possible combination of Subway sandwiches involves considering the various options and components available for each sandwich. Here's a general approach to estimate this cost:\n\n1. **Sandwich Bread Options:** There are several types of bread available, such as Italian, Wheat, Herb & Cheese, etc.\n\n2. **Meats and Proteins:** Subway offers various proteins such as turkey, chicken, beef, ham, and plant-based options.\n\n3. **Cheese Choices:** There are usually a few options like American, Swiss, and cheddar cheeses.\n\n4. **Vegetables:** Subway provides a wide array of vegetables, including lettuce, tomatoes, cucumbers, peppers, onions, and more.\n\n5. **Sauces and Condiments:** Options include mayonnaise, mustard, barbecue, and others.\n\n6. **Additional Toppings:** Options like bacon, avocado, or extra cheese might be available at an extra cost.\n\n7. **Size Options:** Subway sandwiches typically come in 6-inch and footlong sizes.\n\nTo compute the total number of combinations, you would multiply the number of choices for each element (bread, meat, cheese, vegetables, sauces, additional toppings) and then consider the different sizes. For example:\n\n- If Subway offers 5 types of bread, 8 proteins, 3 cheeses, 10 vegetable options, 5 sauces, and 2 sizes, this results in a massive number of combinations (especially if you consider permutations of vegetable and sauce combinations).\n\nUnfortunately, the exact number of combinations and their prices can be highly variable due to regional menu differences, limited-time offers, and pricing changes, so providing a precise number is challenging without specific details.\n\nHowever, Subway often allows customers to build sandwiches according to their preferences, which makes the potential total number of combinations extraordinarily high and likely impractical to purchase or calculate cost-wise, because the variability in number and permutations would result in millions of potential combinations.\n\nTo attempt any calculation for an extensive experiment like this, it would be best to:\n\n1. Determine the menu specifics for the Subway location of interest.\n2. Calculate the number of combinations given the options at that location.\n3. Estimate the cost for the average sandwich based on local prices and calculate a rough estimate by multiplying the average cost by the number of combinations.\n\nA practical approach would be to accept that trying every combination is not economically feasible and focus on trying specific types that interest you the most.",
